<li id="cite_note-93"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-93">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><i>Butler's lives of the saints: the third millennium</i> by Paul Burns, Alban Butler 2001 <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-86012-383-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-86012-383-5">978-0-86012-383-5</a> p. 252</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Morgan1996-94"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Morgan1996_94-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFMorgan1996" class="citation book cs1">Morgan, David (1996). <i>Icons of American Protestantism: The Art of Warner Sallman</i>. Yale University Press. p.&#160;62. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-300-06342-4" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-300-06342-4"><bdi>978-0-300-06342-4</bdi></a>. <q>Sallman always insisted that his initial sketch of Jesus was the result of spiritual "picturization," a miraculous vision that he received late one night. "The answer came at 2 A.M., January 1924," he wrote. "It came as a vision in response to my prayer to God in a despairing situation." The situation was a deadline: Sallman had been commissioned to paint the February cover for the <i>Covenant Companion</i>, the monthly magazine of the Evangelical Covenant Church, and he had artist's block for weeks. The February issue was focusing on Christian youth, and Sallman's assignment was to provide an inspirational image of Christ that would "challenge our young people." "I mused over it for a long time in prayer and meditation," Sallman recalled, "seeking for something which would catch the eye and convey the message of the Christian gospel on the cover."<span class="cs1-kern-right"></span></q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Icons+of+American+Protestantism%3A+The+Art+of+Warner+Sallman&amp;rft.pages=62&amp;rft.pub=Yale+University+Press&amp;rft.date=1996&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-300-06342-4&amp;rft.aulast=Morgan&amp;rft.aufirst=David&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADepiction+of+Jesus" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-95"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-95">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFOtto_F.A._Meinardus,_Ph.D.1997" class="citation journal cs1">Otto F.A. Meinardus, Ph.D. (Fall 1997). "Theological Issues of the Coptic Orthodox Inculturation in Western Society". <i>Coptic Church Review</i>. <b>18</b> (3). <a href="/wiki/ISSN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISSN (identifier)">ISSN</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.worldcat.org/issn/0273-3269">0273-3269</a>. <q>An interesting case of inculturation occurred on Monday, November 11, 1991 when the 12-year-old Isaac Ayoub of Houston, Texas, suffering from leukemia, saw that the eyes of Jesus in the famous Sallman <i>Head of Christ</i> began moving and shedding an oily liquid like tears. On the same day, Fr. Ishaq Soliman, the Coptic priest of St. Mark's Coptic Church in Houston, testified to the miracles. On the following day, Dr. Atef Rizkalla, the family physician, examined the youth and certified that there were no traces of leukemia. Sallman's <i>Head of Christ</i> was exhibited in the Coptic Church and more than 50,000 people visited the church. Two Coptic bishops, Anbâ Tadros of Port Said and Anbâ Yuhanna of Cairo verified the story.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Coptic+Church+Review&amp;rft.atitle=Theological+Issues+of+the+Coptic+Orthodox+Inculturation+in+Western+Society&amp;rft.ssn=fall&amp;rft.volume=18&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.date=1997&amp;rft.issn=0273-3269&amp;rft.au=Otto+F.A.+Meinardus%2C+Ph.D.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADepiction+of+Jesus" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Meinardus2006-96"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Meinardus2006_96-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Meinardus2006_96-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFMeinardus2006" class="citation book cs1">Meinardus, Otto F. A. (2006). <i>Christians In Egypt: Orthodox, Catholic, and Protestant Communities – Past and Present</i>. American University in Cairo Press. p.&#160;70. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-61797-262-1" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-61797-262-1"><bdi>978-1-61797-262-1</bdi></a>. <q>An interesting case of inculturation took place on Monday, November 11, 1991 when the twelve-year-old Isaac Ayoub of Houston, Texas, suffering from leukemia, saw that the eyes of Jesus in the famous Sallman "Head of Christ" began moving and shedding an oily liquid like tears. On the same day, Father Ishaq Soliman, the Coptic priest of St. Mark's Coptic Church in Houston, testified to the miracles. On the following day, Dr. Atef Rizkalla, the family physician, examined the youth and certified that there were no traces of leukemia. Sallman's <i>Head of Christ</i> was exhibited in the Coptic Church and more than fifty thousand people visited the church. Two Coptic bishops, Bishop Tadros of Port Said and Bishop Yuhanna of Cairo, verified the story.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Christians+In+Egypt%3A+Orthodox%2C+Catholic%2C+and+Protestant+Communities+%E2%80%93+Past+and+Present&amp;rft.pages=70&amp;rft.pub=American+University+in+Cairo+Press&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-61797-262-1&amp;rft.aulast=Meinardus&amp;rft.aufirst=Otto+F.+A.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADepiction+of+Jesus" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Morgan96-97"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Morgan96_97-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFMorgan1996" class="citation book cs1">Morgan, David (1996). <i>The Art of Warner Sallman</i>. Yale University Press. p.&#160;192. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-300-06342-4" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-300-06342-4"><bdi>978-0-300-06342-4</bdi></a>. <q>Articles published in popular religious magazines during this time gathered together in an obviously didactic way several anecdotes concerning the power of Sallman's picture among nonwhites, non-Christians, and those exhibiting unacceptable behavior. We read of a white businessman, for instance, in a remote jungle, assaulted by a vicious group of headhunters who demand that he remove his clothes. In going through his billfold, they discover a small reproduction of Sallman's Christ, quickly apologize, then vanish "into the jungle without inflicting further harm." A second article relates the story of the thief who aborted his misdeed when he saw the <i>Head of Christ</i> on a living room wall. Another tells of the conversion of a Jewish woman on her deathbed, when a hospital chaplain shows her Sallman's picture.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Art+of+Warner+Sallman&amp;rft.pages=192&amp;rft.pub=Yale+University+Press&amp;rft.date=1996&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-300-06342-4&amp;rft.aulast=Morgan&amp;rft.aufirst=David&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADepiction+of+Jesus" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Lippy1994-98"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Lippy1994_98-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFLippy1994" class="citation book cs1">Lippy, Charles H. (1994). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=3yB1R5485dUC&amp;pg=PA185"><i>Being Religious, American Style: A History of Popular Religiosity in the United States</i></a>. Greenwood Publishing Group. p.&#160;185. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-313-27895-2" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-313-27895-2"><bdi>978-0-313-27895-2</bdi></a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">30 April</span> 2014</span>. <q>Of these one stands out as having deeply impressed itself of the American religious consciousness: the <i>Head of Christ</i> by artist Warner Sallman (1892–1968). Originally sketched in charcoal as a cover illustration for the <i>Covenant Companion</i>, the magazine of the Swedish Evangelical Mission Covenant of America denomination, and based on an image of Jesus in a painting by the French artist Leon Augustin Lhermitte, Sallman's <i>Head of Christ</i> was painted in 1940. In half a century, it had been produced more than five hundred million times in formats ranging from large-scale copies for use in churches to wallet-sized ones that individuals could carry with them at all times.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Being+Religious%2C+American+Style%3A+A+History+of+Popular+Religiosity+in+the+United+States&amp;rft.pages=185&amp;rft.pub=Greenwood+Publishing+Group&amp;rft.date=1994&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-313-27895-2&amp;rft.aulast=Lippy&amp;rft.aufirst=Charles+H.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D3yB1R5485dUC%26pg%3DPA185&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADepiction+of+Jesus" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-BlumHarvey2012-99"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-BlumHarvey2012_99-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFBlumHarvey2012" class="citation book cs1">Blum, Edward J.; Harvey, Paul (2012). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=TPSB1QZkFU0C&amp;pg=PA211"><i>Color of Christ</i></a>. UNC Press Books. p.&#160;211. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-8078-3737-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-8078-3737-5"><bdi>978-0-8078-3737-5</bdi></a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">30 April</span> 2014</span>. <q>By the 1990s, Sallman's Head of Christ had been printed more than 500 million times and had achieved global iconic status.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Color+of+Christ&amp;rft.pages=211&amp;rft.pub=UNC+Press+Books&amp;rft.date=2012&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-8078-3737-5&amp;rft.aulast=Blum&amp;rft.aufirst=Edward+J.&amp;rft.au=Harvey%2C+Paul&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DTPSB1QZkFU0C%26pg%3DPA211&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADepiction+of+Jesus" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-WCPO-100"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-WCPO_100-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite class="citation news cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130629192543/http://www.wcpo.com/dpp/news/region_north_cincinnati/monroe/Construction-to-begin-on-new-Jesus-statue-along-I-75#ixzz1y1CWlU3h">"Construction progressing on new Jesus statue along I-75"</a>. <i>WCPO</i>. 15 June 2012. Archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.wcpo.com/dpp/news/region_north_cincinnati/monroe/Construction-to-begin-on-new-Jesus-statue-along-I-75#ixzz1y1CWlU3h">the original</a> on 29 June 2013<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">7 September</span> 2012</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=WCPO&amp;rft.atitle=Construction+progressing+on+new+Jesus+statue+along+I-75&amp;rft.date=2012-06-15&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.wcpo.com%2Fdpp%2Fnews%2Fregion_north_cincinnati%2Fmonroe%2FConstruction-to-begin-on-new-Jesus-statue-along-I-75%23ixzz1y1CWlU3h&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADepiction+of+Jesus" class="Z3988"></span></span>
